{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2385"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2385"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.1,0.06,0.66,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2385"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109928"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2385"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2385"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92286"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1820"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37199"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109928"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman comes to the GP clinic with a 5-day history of mild shortness of breath with exertion. She has an associated cough and productive sputum three days ago. The sputum was non-bloody and white in colour. Prior to this episode of shortness of breath, she had a runny nose, mild headaches and generalised muscle fatigue. She had no fever, chills or rigor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer 8-year-old son had a fever and purulent cough, and an associated exanthematous rash two weeks ago which had resolved spontaneously. She does not smoke and drinks two standard drinks a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well and rested. Her vital signs are stable. On lung examination, bilateral scattered wheeze is heard at both lung bases and no increase in vocal resonance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prescribe oral azithromycin","Prescribe oral amoxicillin and clavulanic acid","Prescribe inhaled long-acting beta-agonist (LABA)/ inhaled corticosteroids (ICS) with a metered-dose inhaler (MDI)","Supportive treatment only","Prescribe salbutamol nebulised"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with shortness of breath and cough on exertion following upper respiratory tract infection symptoms. The lack of fever and no signs of lung consolidation on physical examination would suggest acute bronchitis. This is commonly caused by a virus (more than 90% of the cases), such as influenza A and B, parainfluenza and adenovirus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn acute bronchitis, antibiotic treatment is not necessary and \u003Cstrong\u003Esupportive treatment is sufficient\u003C/strong\u003E. Antibiotic use in acute bronchitis is unnecessary and should not be used. Such wanton use of antibiotics only increases the chance of development of antimicrobial resistance. Supportive treatment consists of adequate hydration and rest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAzithromycin and amoxicillin-clavulanate acid are used for treatment for community acquired pneumonia. Pneumonia may present with shortness of breath and production cough. However, the patient does not have other suggestive signs of pneumonia such as fever, purulent sputum and crcackles or reduced breath sounds on lung auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of acute bronchitis is mainly focused on symptomatic management. Steroids and bronchodilators have no proven efficacy in an uncomplicated acute bronchitis. This patient appears well with stable vital signs and therefore steroids and nebulised salbutamol is unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For most patients with acute bronchitis, supportive treatment alone is quite sufficient.","Antibiotics are not indicated for uncomplicated acute bronchitis, as most cases are viral in origin."],"references":["Wenzel RP, Fowler AA 3rd. Clinical practice. Acute bronchitis. N Engl J Med 2006; 355:2125. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17108344/","Albert RH. Diagnosis and treatment of acute bronchitis. Am Fam Physician. 2010\u202fDec\u202f1;82(11):1345\u20131350  Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2010/1201/p1345.html","MacKay DN. Treatment of acute bronchitis in adults without underlying lung disease. J Gen Intern Med 1996; 11:557. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8905509/","Singh A, Avula A, Zahn E. Acute Bronchitis. [Updated 2024 Mar 9]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448067/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92286"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2385"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92286"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T16:40:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T16:43:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2385"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109928"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic